```csharp
[Header("Headbob Settings")]
[SerializeField] private float headBobDuration = 0.5f;
[SerializeField] private float headBobHeightAmplitude = 0.1f;
[SerializeField] private float headBobRotationAmplitude = 3f;

private IEnumerator JumpHeadBob()
{
    float timeElapsed = 0;
    Vector3 initialCameraPosition = playerCamera.transform.localPosition;

    while (timeElapsed < headBobDuration)
    {
        float yOffset = Mathf.Sin(timeElapsed / headBobDuration * Mathf.PI) * headBobHeightAmplitude;
        playerCamera.transform.localPosition = new Vector3(initialCameraPosition.x, initialCameraPosition.y + yOffset, initialCameraPosition.z);

        float zRotation = Mathf.Sin(timeElapsed / headBobDuration * Mathf.PI * 2) * headBobRotationAmplitude;

        // Get the current X rotation of the camera.
        float xRotation = playerCamera.transform.localRotation.eulerAngles.x;

        // Apply the updated rotation.
        playerCamera.transform.localRotation = Quaternion.Euler(xRotation, 0, zRotation);

        timeElapsed += Time.deltaTime;
        yield return null;
    }

    playerCamera.transform.localPosition = initialCameraPosition;
}
```

Now, the `headBobDuration`, `headBobHeightAmplitude`, and `headBobRotationAmplitude` variables can be edited directly from the Inspector in Unity.

Unfortunately, Unity doesn't support collapsible headers out of the box. However, you can achieve collapsible sections by using custom Editor scripting. We can create a custom editor script to organize your headers and make them collapsible.

Here's an example of how to create a custom editor script for your MonoBehaviour:

1. First, create a new C# script named "MyMonobehaviourEditor" and put the following code inside it:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using UnityEditor;

[CustomEditor(typeof(MyMonobehaviour))]
public class MyMonobehaviourEditor : Editor
{
    private bool showHeadbobSettings = true;

    public override void OnInspectorGUI()
    {
        MyMonobehaviour myScript = (MyMonobehaviour)target;

        // Draw default inspector properties.
        DrawDefaultInspector();

        // Add collapsible Headbob Settings header.
        showHeadbobSettings = EditorGUILayout.Foldout(showHeadbobSettings, "Headbob Settings");
        if (showHeadbobSettings)
        {
            EditorGUI.indentLevel++;
            myScript.headBobDuration = EditorGUILayout.FloatField("Headbob Duration", myScript.headBobDuration);
            myScript.headBobHeightAmplitude = EditorGUILayout.FloatField("Headbob Height Amplitude", myScript.headBobHeightAmplitude);
            myScript.headBobRotationAmplitude = EditorGUILayout.FloatField("Headbob Rotation Amplitude", myScript.headBobRotationAmplitude);
            EditorGUI.indentLevel--;
        }
    }
}
```

Make sure to replace "MyMonobehaviour" with the name of the script that contains your headbob variables.

2. In your original MonoBehaviour script, remove the `[Header("Headbob Settings")]` line and make the variables `public` instead of `[SerializeField]`.

```csharp
public float headBobDuration = 0.5f;
public float headBobHeightAmplitude = 0.1f;
public float headBobRotationAmplitude = 3f;
```

Now, the "Headbob Settings" header will be collapsible in the Inspector.

You can apply the same concept to create more collapsible headers. Add more variables and sections as needed inside `OnInspectorGUI()` and use `EditorGUILayout.Foldout()` for collapsible headers. Make sure to update variable accessors in the MonoBehaviour script accordingly.

To make it more modular and reusable, you can create a separate static class for custom Editor utilities. This class will contain a generic method to handle collapsible headers for any script.

1. Create a new C# script called "EditorUtilities" and place the following code inside it:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using UnityEditor;

public static class EditorUtilities
{
    public static bool DrawCollapsibleHeader(string title, bool foldout)
    {
        GUIStyle headerStyle = new GUIStyle(EditorStyles.foldout);
        headerStyle.fontSize = 14;
        headerStyle.fontStyle = FontStyle.Bold;

        EditorGUILayout.BeginHorizontal();
        foldout = EditorGUILayout.Foldout(foldout, title, true, headerStyle);

        EditorGUILayout.EndHorizontal();
        return foldout;
    }
}
```

This static class has a method `DrawCollapsibleHeader` which allows you to create collapsible headers that can be used in any custom Editor script.

2. Next, modify your custom Editor script (e.g., MyMonobehaviourEditor) to use the reusable `DrawCollapsibleHeader` function:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using UnityEditor;

[CustomEditor(typeof(MyMonobehaviour))]
public class MyMonobehaviourEditor : Editor
{
    private bool showHeadbobSettings = true;

    public override void OnInspectorGUI()
    {
        MyMonobehaviour myScript = (MyMonobehaviour)target;

        // Draw default inspector properties.
        DrawDefaultInspector();

        // Add collapsible Headbob Settings header.
        showHeadbobSettings = EditorUtilities.DrawCollapsibleHeader("Headbob Settings", showHeadbobSettings);
        if (showHeadbobSettings)
        {
            EditorGUI.indentLevel++;
            myScript.headBobDuration = EditorGUILayout.FloatField("Headbob Duration", myScript.headBobDuration);
            myScript.headBobHeightAmplitude = EditorGUILayout.FloatField("Headbob Height Amplitude", myScript.headBobHeightAmplitude);
            myScript.headBobRotationAmplitude = EditorGUILayout.FloatField("Headbob Rotation Amplitude", myScript.headBobRotationAmplitude);
            EditorGUI.indentLevel--;
        }
    }
}
```

Now, if you want to create collapsible headers in any custom Editor script, you can simply call the `EditorUtilities.DrawCollapsibleHeader` method. This makes it easier to handle multiple headers and keep your code organized.

